 was permeated with a sense of vitality and hope.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHolocaust survivorsxTravelzIsraelzPolandvPersonal narratives. 0aHolocaust survivorszPolandzŁódźxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives. 0aJewszPolandzŁódźxHistoryy20th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618116888zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618116888zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618116888/original  a978-3-11-068814-6 Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA